tudy highlights the tensions and ambivalences of Khmer socialization, with particular emphasis on Khmer conceptions of personhood, morality, and sexuality. Nancy J. Smith-Hefner considers how this cultural heritage influences the performance of Khmer children in American schools and, ultimately, determines Khmer engagement with American culture.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCambodian AmericansxEthnic identityxMassachusettsxBoston. 0aCambodian AmericansxReligionxMassachusettsxBoston. 0aCambodian AmericanszMassachusettszBostonxEthnic identity. 0aCambodian AmericanszMassachusettszBostonxReligion. 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aSmith-Hefner, Nancy J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021349440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092086640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920866423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920866/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles